WEBVTT

00:01.001 --> 00:02.544
<i>Previously on</i> This Is Us...

00:02.627 --> 00:04.421
<i>NICKY:</i>
<i>It was originally for someone else.</i>

00:04.504 --> 00:06.047
The trailer.

00:06.131 --> 00:08.133
Sally.

00:08.216 --> 00:12.095
We, uh, started dating
before I got drafted.

00:12.178 --> 00:14.180
Make me proud, son.

00:14.264 --> 00:16.307
<i>NICKY:</i>
<i>I hated the war.</i>

00:16.391 --> 00:17.600
I hated myself.

00:17.684 --> 00:22.147
<i>And your father tried to clean me up.</i>

00:22.230 --> 00:24.065
He should never have come for me.

00:25.692 --> 00:27.402
This handsome young man right here,

00:27.485 --> 00:29.279
this is Nick.

00:29.362 --> 00:31.781
How about that.

00:33.199 --> 00:35.618
Let me get this straight.

00:35.702 --> 00:38.288
You only named one baby
after your favorite uncle?

00:42.625 --> 00:45.211
(laughs) Uncle Nicky, what are you...
what are you doing here?

00:46.296 --> 00:48.340
Well, I came to see my namesake.

00:48.423 --> 00:50.216
And-and the girl.

00:51.301 --> 00:54.346
Oh. Uh, yeah, of cour...
Yes, come in. Come on in.

00:54.429 --> 00:55.764
-Yeah?
-Yeah, come in.

00:55.847 --> 00:58.350
Well... I mean, I got the invitation

00:58.433 --> 01:01.519
to the kids' baptism,
so, you know, I booked a flight.

01:01.603 --> 01:03.313
KEVIN: Oh. Yeah.

01:03.396 --> 01:05.190
No, I-I guess you didn't see
the Zoom link, then,

01:05.273 --> 01:06.733
on the back of the...

01:06.816 --> 01:09.861
-The what, now?
-Oh, nothing, nothing. It's, uh...

01:09.944 --> 01:11.488
We're glad you're here. This is great.

01:11.571 --> 01:14.115
And this is the first time
you're meeting Madison, right?

01:14.199 --> 01:16.201
Oh, wow. So tiny.

01:16.284 --> 01:20.080
You had twins-- that must
have done a real number on you.

01:20.163 --> 01:22.082
(laughs):
Nice to meet you.

01:22.165 --> 01:23.792
Oh, so, listen,
I know everybody's freaking out

01:23.875 --> 01:25.085
about the virus thing.

01:25.168 --> 01:27.629
I get it. But you don't have to worry.

01:27.712 --> 01:29.881
I have been vaccinated--

01:29.964 --> 01:32.550
twice-- and I-I...

01:32.634 --> 01:35.303
I get tested up the nose twice a week

01:35.387 --> 01:38.056
at the VA for my meetings,
and I didn't eat on the plane,

01:38.139 --> 01:39.391
I-I didn't pee on the plane,
I didn't touch

01:39.474 --> 01:42.143
-a damn thing on the plane.
-(laughs): Okay, understood.

01:43.561 --> 01:45.814
Uncle Nicky, I cannot believe
that you flew across the country

01:45.897 --> 01:48.066
to meet our kids. It's...

01:48.149 --> 01:50.235
(sighs)

01:50.318 --> 01:52.487
It's incredible.

01:55.115 --> 01:57.325
It was nothing.

01:57.409 --> 01:59.369
(intro to "Lonely People" playing)

02:03.665 --> 02:06.459
♪ ♪

02:17.012 --> 02:20.265
♪ <i>This is for all the lonely people</i> ♪

02:21.349 --> 02:22.767
Ah.

02:22.851 --> 02:25.145
♪ <i>Thinking that life has passed them by</i> ♪

02:25.228 --> 02:27.105
Hey, kid, can you talk?

02:27.188 --> 02:29.482
Sure.
I'm just cleaning Matty's disgusting shoes

02:29.566 --> 02:30.942
for his soccer game.

02:31.026 --> 02:32.736
Apparently, it's not a good look
when your kid

02:32.819 --> 02:34.362
<i>comes</i> to the field caked in mud.

02:34.446 --> 02:36.114
Listen, I need your help.

02:36.197 --> 02:38.950
Can you explain to me now, in detail,

02:39.034 --> 02:42.579
how to use, uh, Amazon.com.

02:42.662 --> 02:44.330
♪ <i>All the single people</i> ♪

02:44.414 --> 02:46.416
<i>And speak really slowly.</i>

02:46.499 --> 02:49.461
♪ <i>Thinking that love has left them dry</i> ♪

02:52.797 --> 02:56.259
♪ <i>Don't give up until you</i> ♪

02:56.343 --> 02:59.220
♪ <i>Drink from the silver cup</i> ♪

02:59.304 --> 03:02.390
♪ <i>You never know until you try</i> ♪

03:02.474 --> 03:03.516
<i>♪ Hit it ♪</i>

03:03.600 --> 03:05.602
<i>(harmonica featured)</i>

03:13.735 --> 03:16.279
-How are you with shots?
-I was a medic in Vietnam,

03:16.363 --> 03:19.449
so cut the chitchat and jab me, Doc.

03:21.034 --> 03:22.619
<i>(song continues with piano featured)</i>

03:22.702 --> 03:24.996
Okay, so I'm good? I'm safe?

03:25.080 --> 03:27.957
Not for a while.
And you have to come back in three weeks

03:28.041 --> 03:30.335
-for a second dose.
-There's a second one?

03:30.418 --> 03:32.504
Yep.

03:32.587 --> 03:36.466
♪ <i>This is for all the lonely people</i> ♪

03:39.177 --> 03:40.929
♪ <i>Thinking that life has passed them by</i> ♪

03:41.012 --> 03:43.556
It'll be two weeks
before you're fully protected,

03:43.640 --> 03:46.393
so if you're gonna see anyone,
you need to continue testing.

03:46.476 --> 03:47.936
Got it.

03:48.019 --> 03:49.938
I'm going to California.

03:50.021 --> 03:52.774
My nephew named his kid after me.

03:52.857 --> 03:54.067
That's nice.

03:54.150 --> 03:57.112
♪ <i>Never give you up</i> ♪

03:57.195 --> 04:00.156
♪ <i>You never know until you try.</i> ♪

04:02.534 --> 04:04.661
<i>DUKE: Hey, that's a good view</i>
<i>of Mr. Collins down there.</i>

04:04.744 --> 04:06.371
<i>We can finally see him again.</i>

04:06.454 --> 04:07.706
<i>(beeps)</i>

04:07.789 --> 04:09.874
Hmm?

04:09.958 --> 04:12.836
What is it?
Looks like a spider.

04:12.919 --> 04:15.797
No, Pop, i-it's the lunar module.

04:15.880 --> 04:17.799
The LM.
It's the spacecraft

04:17.882 --> 04:19.134
that Buzz and Armstrong are in right now.

04:19.217 --> 04:20.427
See, it-it's two parts

04:20.510 --> 04:22.387
that separate--
the top is the "ascent stage,"

04:22.470 --> 04:24.264
where the astronauts are,

04:24.347 --> 04:28.143
and the "descent stage"
has the rocket power in it. See?

04:28.226 --> 04:30.603
I even used pieces
from my old World War II bomber

04:30.687 --> 04:32.147
model planes to build it.

04:32.230 --> 04:33.773
Here, let me see it.

04:35.942 --> 04:37.444
I like the ladder.

04:37.527 --> 04:38.820
Thanks.

04:38.903 --> 04:41.114
-STANLEY: It's nice.
-Hey.

04:41.197 --> 04:42.532
I didn't miss it, did I?

04:42.615 --> 04:44.409
Jack, no, the LM hasn't even landed yet,

04:44.492 --> 04:46.494
so the astronauts won't walk for hours.

04:46.578 --> 04:48.455
Hey, Pop.

04:48.538 --> 04:49.831
"Hey" back.

04:49.914 --> 04:51.416
What, are you hoarding your beers now?

04:51.499 --> 04:54.711
Jacky!
Oh, so glad you came.

04:54.794 --> 04:57.172
Hi, Mom.
You look great.

04:57.255 --> 04:59.132
<i>(Moon landing broadcast continues)</i>

04:59.215 --> 05:00.675
Hey.

05:00.759 --> 05:03.261
Nicky, the meatballs on the right
don't have olives, okay?

05:03.345 --> 05:05.013
Oh, thanks, Mom.

05:05.096 --> 05:08.725
Unbelievable. You got to make
two of everything for this kid?

05:08.808 --> 05:10.810
I'd make four of everything if he wanted.

05:10.894 --> 05:12.729
STANLEY:
Jack, have a seat

05:12.812 --> 05:14.814
next to your little sister--
it's starting.

05:17.776 --> 05:19.652
<i>BUZZ ALDRIN:</i>
<i>Okay, engine stopped.</i>

05:19.736 --> 05:21.821
<i>ACA out of detent.</i>

05:21.905 --> 05:23.114
<i>Remote control both autos,</i>

05:23.198 --> 05:24.574
<i>descent engine command override off.</i>

05:24.657 --> 05:27.077
<i>-Engine arm off.</i>
<i>-We're home.</i>

05:27.160 --> 05:29.079
<i>413 is in.</i>

05:29.162 --> 05:31.206
<i>WALTER CRONKITE:</i>
<i>Man on the Moon!</i>

05:31.289 --> 05:33.416
<i>MAN:</i>
<i>We copy you down,</i> Eagle.

05:33.500 --> 05:35.126
<i>NEIL ARMSTRONG:</i>
<i>Houston, uh...</i>

05:35.210 --> 05:36.795
♪ ♪

05:36.878 --> 05:38.713
<i>Tranquility Base here.</i>

05:38.797 --> 05:40.215
<i>The</i> Eagle <i>has landed.</i>

05:40.298 --> 05:42.634
<i>MAN:</i>
<i>Roger, Tranquility.</i>

05:42.717 --> 05:44.302
<i>We copy you on the ground.</i>
<i>You got a bunch of guys</i>

05:44.386 --> 05:46.596
<i>about to turn blue.</i>
<i>We're breathing again.</i>

05:46.680 --> 05:49.265
<i>-(Cronkite laughing)</i>
<i>-Thanks a lot.</i>

05:49.349 --> 05:51.768
<i>-CRONKITE: Oh, boy!</i>
<i>-Thank you.</i>

05:51.851 --> 05:55.563
-♪ ♪
<i>-(broadcast continues indistinctly)</i>

05:56.606 --> 05:58.441
-Want one?
-No.

05:58.525 --> 06:00.110
No, I got to get home soon.

06:02.070 --> 06:03.738
Have you... you thought about moving out

06:03.822 --> 06:06.116
of Mom and Dad's house at any point?

06:06.199 --> 06:07.784
No.

06:07.867 --> 06:10.203
Unlike you, I-I like having hot water.

06:10.286 --> 06:12.080
Yeah, but, Nick, come on,
you don't want to be

06:12.163 --> 06:15.583
Dad's lapdog, fetching him beers
the rest of his life, huh?

06:15.667 --> 06:18.503
I mean, you got to leave
the nest at some point.

06:18.586 --> 06:20.505
Yeah, well, I may be
forcibly removed from the nest

06:20.588 --> 06:23.341
-if I get drafted to Vietnam this year.
-You're not getting drafted.

06:23.425 --> 06:25.468
-I could.
-You're not getting drafted.

06:25.552 --> 06:27.679
And also, it's really not that bad

06:27.762 --> 06:30.348
living at Mom and Dad's right now.

06:30.432 --> 06:31.850
I mean...

06:31.933 --> 06:34.769
(whispers): he's a lot better
with her when I'm around.

06:34.853 --> 06:36.730
You wouldn't know, trust me.

06:37.772 --> 06:39.232
(chuckles)

06:39.315 --> 06:41.651
Could you at least just...
Do me a favor.

06:41.735 --> 06:44.404
Get yourself a girlfriend or something.

06:44.487 --> 06:46.823
(scoffs) Yeah, sure,
you got Raquel Welch's number?

06:46.906 --> 06:48.992
Oh, come on, there's got to be a nice girl

06:49.075 --> 06:51.953
works the vet clinic with you, right?

06:54.622 --> 06:56.207
Oh, there is.

06:56.291 --> 06:57.334
Yeah.

06:58.335 --> 06:59.919
Yeah.

07:00.003 --> 07:01.296
Sally.

07:01.379 --> 07:04.758
Sally. Nick...

07:04.841 --> 07:06.718
there is a guy...

07:06.801 --> 07:10.055
walking on the Moon, right now.

07:10.138 --> 07:12.432
Ask Sally out on a date.
Get the hell out of the house.

07:12.515 --> 07:14.976
Come on, if he can do it,
you can do it. Okay?

07:15.060 --> 07:16.644
(patting Nicky's back)

07:20.982 --> 07:22.442
(groans)

07:23.485 --> 07:25.653
Whoa. Wait.

07:25.737 --> 07:27.947
Aren't you supposed to fold the corners

07:28.031 --> 07:30.200
-into little triangles?
-Would you like to take over?

07:30.283 --> 07:32.243
I'm just saying,
I think you could be a little neater.

07:32.327 --> 07:34.329
You know?
It took me weeks to build this gift,

07:34.412 --> 07:36.498
and I suck at wrapping, not that...

07:36.581 --> 07:38.917
babies are gonna know
the difference, but, you know,

07:39.000 --> 07:41.711
-still.
-I'm very curious about these mystery gifts.

07:41.795 --> 07:43.546
I'll mail you a photo.

07:43.630 --> 07:44.798
I was an intelligence officer.

07:44.881 --> 07:46.841
I could get this out of you
if I wanted to.

07:46.925 --> 07:48.968
-Yeah, good luck with that.
-(scoffs)

07:49.052 --> 07:50.762
-All right.
-All right.

07:50.845 --> 07:52.347
Is this up to your standards?

07:57.435 --> 07:59.104
Yeah.

07:59.187 --> 08:00.939
I am proud of you.

08:01.022 --> 08:02.357
You know?
Getting out of your routine

08:02.440 --> 08:04.192
and getting out of this trailer, it's a...

08:04.275 --> 08:05.735
-it's all a big deal.
-Thank you.

08:09.197 --> 08:11.324
No, kid, really, thank you.

08:13.118 --> 08:14.786
I haven't been able

08:14.869 --> 08:18.081
<i>to count on many people</i>
<i>since I got back from the war.</i>

08:18.164 --> 08:21.084
(phone ringing)

08:21.167 --> 08:23.169
(birds chirping)

08:27.507 --> 08:29.217
-(ringing continues)
-(groans softly)

08:34.597 --> 08:35.515
(exhales)

08:35.598 --> 08:37.308
-Hello?
<i>-Don't hang up, Pearson.</i>

08:37.392 --> 08:39.227
<i>It's Townie.</i>

08:40.395 --> 08:41.938
<i>Vietnam?</i>

08:42.022 --> 08:43.940
<i>-Alpha Company Third Squad?</i>
-Yeah, yeah.

08:44.024 --> 08:46.026
No, I know who you are.
What the hell do you want?

08:46.109 --> 08:49.904
I'm doing okay.
Thanks for asking.

08:49.988 --> 08:53.158
God, you try to do a guy a favor.

08:53.241 --> 08:55.243
<i>I'm calling because some</i>
<i>of the guys from the area</i>

08:55.326 --> 08:57.120
<i>are getting together to have a few drinks</i>

08:57.203 --> 08:59.622
<i>and celebrate</i>
<i>Lieutenant Sheehan's engagement.</i>

08:59.706 --> 09:03.126
<i>I drove all the way from Chicago.</i>

09:04.169 --> 09:06.671
I know you don't go
to these things, but...

09:06.755 --> 09:08.548
it's in your neck of the woods.

09:08.631 --> 09:10.300
Erie.

09:11.968 --> 09:14.220
I heard Jack'll be there.

09:19.642 --> 09:22.103
I haven't seen Jack in years.

09:22.187 --> 09:24.230
<i>At least write down the address.</i>

09:26.649 --> 09:30.111
Fine. Just go slow, 'cause
I-I got a splitting headache

09:30.195 --> 09:32.113
right now.

09:32.197 --> 09:35.033
<i>777 Lake Pleasant Road,</i>

09:35.116 --> 09:37.494
<i>Erie, PA.</i>

09:37.577 --> 09:39.579
♪ ♪

09:58.098 --> 09:59.891
(exhales)

09:59.974 --> 10:02.310
(sighs)

10:02.394 --> 10:03.561
(knocking)

10:03.645 --> 10:05.855
Ready, old man?

10:05.939 --> 10:07.315
(sighs)

10:07.399 --> 10:09.317
Ready as I'll ever be.

10:09.401 --> 10:11.569
Okay.

10:19.953 --> 10:22.914
Pumpkin, you are a landlord

10:22.997 --> 10:24.958
to an entire colony of fleas.

10:25.041 --> 10:27.335
-(barks softly)
-And you need a bath.

10:27.419 --> 10:29.754
Okay?
You have to work with me here.

10:29.838 --> 10:32.590
-(whines)
-Bath time. (mutters)

10:32.674 --> 10:34.384
-You got to work with me, baby.
-(whines)

10:34.467 --> 10:36.636
Bath time for Pumpkin!
No?

10:36.720 --> 10:39.639
-Aah. Okay. Okay, Pumpkin.
-Do you need some help?

10:39.723 --> 10:41.641
-(Pumpkin whimpers)
-Sally. Hi.

10:41.725 --> 10:44.019
Yeah, Pumpkin needs a bath,

10:44.102 --> 10:46.855
but I don't think we can lift her,
even if we both tried.

10:46.938 --> 10:48.356
Oh.

10:48.440 --> 10:50.608
-She's very stubborn.
-Yeah.

10:50.692 --> 10:53.820
She's a willful lady, all right.

10:53.903 --> 10:56.698
You can't force a willful lady
to do anything.

10:56.781 --> 10:58.366
There's only one thing to do.

11:00.368 --> 11:01.619
Hmm?

11:09.085 --> 11:11.546
-Okay. -(Pumpkin chuffs)
-(clears throat)

11:11.629 --> 11:13.465
Oh, this water feels so warm.

11:13.548 --> 11:15.050
It's so warm and refreshing.

11:15.133 --> 11:16.760
This feels great.

11:16.843 --> 11:19.012
Come on, Pumpkin!
Come on.

11:19.095 --> 11:20.388
Oh, good girl.

11:20.472 --> 11:22.390
Come on.
Oh, yeah, good girl.

11:22.474 --> 11:26.102
Yes. Come here, baby.
Come on.

11:26.186 --> 11:28.104
-Good girl.
-You're so good.

11:28.188 --> 11:30.565
Cover up your eyes,
'cause I'm gonna put it on your head.

11:30.648 --> 11:33.818
Good girl. You're so good!
(laughs)

11:33.902 --> 11:37.489
There is slobber all over.

11:37.572 --> 11:39.574
-(Sally laughs)
-Ah.

11:40.575 --> 11:42.952
(clears throat)

11:43.036 --> 11:45.163
Water's so healing, no?

11:45.246 --> 11:48.375
Yeah, yeah, totally.
So healing.

11:48.458 --> 11:50.919
(gasps) Did you see the men
on the Moon last night?

11:51.002 --> 11:54.297
I thought it was poetic,
and it was sort of surreal.

11:54.381 --> 11:56.383
Yeah, it was.

11:56.466 --> 11:58.343
And if you thought that was exciting,

11:58.426 --> 12:01.971
in two days, the module's gonna
come zooming back to Earth

12:02.055 --> 12:04.265
with the astronauts in it
going 25,000 miles per hour,

12:04.349 --> 12:06.601
and everybody's hoping
that it doesn't, um,

12:06.685 --> 12:08.728
disintegrate or bounce back into space.

12:08.812 --> 12:11.773
-Whoa. That's so intense.
-Yeah.

12:11.856 --> 12:13.233
(clears throat)

12:13.316 --> 12:16.069
I'm driving up to Mount Washington tonight

12:16.152 --> 12:18.988
to go look at the Moon.

12:19.072 --> 12:21.116
Do you ever do that kind of a thing?

12:21.199 --> 12:23.618
Um...

12:23.702 --> 12:25.870
I'm a Cancer, so, uh,

12:25.954 --> 12:28.665
I've always felt very close to the Moon.

12:30.417 --> 12:32.252
Far out.
(laughs)

12:32.335 --> 12:33.795
Uh...

12:34.838 --> 12:37.215
Yeah, uh...

12:37.298 --> 12:40.844
Well, I... You should have
a great night, but I-I...

12:40.927 --> 12:43.555
My brother's probably waiting
for me, so...

12:43.638 --> 12:45.015
-Okay.
-Bye.

12:45.098 --> 12:47.434
Bye.
(clears throat)

12:49.853 --> 12:51.771
-Hey.
-Hey. Hi.

12:51.855 --> 12:53.857
Hi.
Uh, Sally, I'm Jack.

12:53.940 --> 12:55.692
I'm Nicky's brother.

12:55.775 --> 13:00.238
Jack. You have a very proud,
determined energy. Cancer?

13:00.321 --> 13:03.616
Uh... no.
I'm... fine.

13:03.700 --> 13:05.952
Uh, listen, I didn't mean
to eavesdrop, but

13:06.036 --> 13:07.454
I overheard you say
that you're gonna be, um,

13:07.537 --> 13:09.581
-checking out the Moon tonight.
-Jack?

13:09.664 --> 13:11.875
Um, there is no better person
to do that with

13:11.958 --> 13:14.669
than my brother Nick.
I mean, this guy-- he knows...

13:14.753 --> 13:18.048
Jack... I'm perfectly capable
of asking your brother out

13:18.131 --> 13:20.675
-all on my own.
-Yeah.

13:20.759 --> 13:23.011
-SALLY: Nicky...
-Uh...

13:23.094 --> 13:24.637
...how would you like to come meet Pearl

13:24.721 --> 13:26.306
and gaze at the Moon with us tonight?

13:28.099 --> 13:29.893
Yeah.

13:29.976 --> 13:31.770
Yeah, I... I would love that.

13:31.853 --> 13:33.396
Groovy.

13:36.232 --> 13:38.234
Here's my address.

13:39.986 --> 13:42.238
Okay, um...

13:44.157 --> 13:45.742
Oh.
Yeah, bye.

13:45.825 --> 13:47.786
-JACK: Thank you.
-I'll see ya.

13:49.329 --> 13:51.873
-Who's Pearl?
-Who cares?

13:53.917 --> 13:56.503
Just remember, you got to take
your shoes off at security now.

13:56.586 --> 13:58.463
Oh.
What an idiotic country.

13:58.546 --> 13:59.923
You sure you don't want to call Kevin?

14:00.006 --> 14:01.299
He's got two newborns.

14:01.383 --> 14:03.635
I mean, a heads-up might be nice.

14:03.718 --> 14:05.345
-Yeah.
-Someone should know

14:05.428 --> 14:06.971
-you're traveling across the country.
-You know.

14:07.055 --> 14:09.057
Someone in your family should know.

14:09.140 --> 14:10.767
Cassidy, come on.
Give me a break.

14:10.850 --> 14:12.560
I haven't been on an airplane

14:12.644 --> 14:15.021
since I got medevaced out of Vietnam.

14:15.105 --> 14:16.731
(sighs):
Oh.

14:16.815 --> 14:18.400
You know, in case I don't make it,

14:18.483 --> 14:20.610
I don't want to disappoint him.
Can't do that to him.

14:21.903 --> 14:24.406
-Just remember to breathe, okay?
-Mm-hmm.

14:25.448 --> 14:27.242
Yeah.

14:27.325 --> 14:29.327
-WOMAN: Next in line.
<i>-MAN (over P.A.): Remove your shoes,</i>

14:29.411 --> 14:30.787
<i>and place them in the bins provided.</i>

14:30.870 --> 14:32.414
Move forward.

14:32.497 --> 14:34.833
(indistinct voice over P.A.)

14:34.916 --> 14:36.292
Mm-hmm.

14:37.585 --> 14:39.170
You're all set.

14:39.254 --> 14:42.924
(indistinct voice over P.A.)

14:45.218 --> 14:47.178
<i>MAN (over P.A.):</i>
<i>I.D. and boarding passes...</i>

14:49.514 --> 14:51.182
MAN:
Uh, sir, step on up.

14:52.225 --> 14:53.268
-(device beeps)
-Sir?

14:53.351 --> 14:54.394
Huh?

14:54.477 --> 14:56.229
Arms up, please.

14:58.023 --> 15:00.025
-Oh.
-(whirring)

15:01.568 --> 15:03.486
WOMAN:
Sir, is-is this your box?

15:03.570 --> 15:05.697
Yeah. Why?

15:05.780 --> 15:08.241
Wait!
Okay, it's very, very fragile,

15:08.324 --> 15:09.743
-so please be careful.
-I'm sorry.

15:09.826 --> 15:11.536
-I'm gonna have to unwrap it.
-What?! No!

15:11.619 --> 15:12.787
-Come on, don't... Aah!
-(paper ripping)

15:12.871 --> 15:15.957
Ah.
Oh, come on.

15:16.041 --> 15:18.626
(muttering)

15:22.464 --> 15:25.675
-Ah.
-I'm sorry, sir, but you can't take these on the flight.

15:25.759 --> 15:27.802
No more than 3.4 ounces of liquid.

15:27.886 --> 15:29.804
If you give us an address,
we can mail them.

15:29.888 --> 15:32.682
I can't go there emptyhanded.

15:32.766 --> 15:34.517
Look, what if I just
dump the liquid, okay?

15:34.601 --> 15:36.061
-Oh...
-Yeah, I'm gonna just...

15:36.144 --> 15:37.520
Look, I'm gonna do that,
it'll take two seconds.

15:37.604 --> 15:40.315
-Sir, what are you doing?
-Is that okay? (grunts)

15:40.398 --> 15:42.108
Oh, God!

15:42.192 --> 15:44.652
Oh, no, no!

16:01.461 --> 16:03.463
(crickets chirping)

16:06.341 --> 16:08.927
-Oh.
-(car horn tooting)

16:09.010 --> 16:10.887
Okay. Sorry.

16:10.970 --> 16:13.348
-Hey! (laughs)
-Sorry.

16:13.431 --> 16:14.557
Hi. (laughs)

16:14.641 --> 16:16.768
-Hi. Sally? Hi.
-(shrieks) You found us!

16:16.851 --> 16:18.353
NICKY: Oh, yeah.

16:18.436 --> 16:20.689
Oh. Sorry if I freaked you out
with the honking.

16:20.772 --> 16:22.691
It's just Pearl's got
to make her presence known.

16:24.025 --> 16:25.860
-Oh, Pearl's your van?
-Mm-hmm.

16:25.944 --> 16:27.779
-Oh.
-Do you want to get inside her?

16:27.862 --> 16:29.823
-Come on!
-What?

16:29.906 --> 16:31.700
-Um...
-Come on, come on, come on!

16:31.783 --> 16:34.911
Ah. Oh, boy.

16:34.994 --> 16:38.206
-Come on in. -(wind chimes tinkle)
-(both laugh)

16:38.289 --> 16:41.042
Make yourself at home, man.

16:41.126 --> 16:45.922
♪ <i>And talk about the things</i>
<i>we did today...</i> ♪

16:46.006 --> 16:48.174
Oh. These are great.

16:48.258 --> 16:51.219
SALLY:
Oh, these are my photographs.

16:51.302 --> 16:55.098
Pearl and I have been all over together.

16:55.181 --> 16:59.310
Yeah, we started in Kansas
and got to Pittsburgh

16:59.394 --> 17:02.814
and have gone pretty much
everywhere in between.

17:02.897 --> 17:04.816
Oh.

17:04.899 --> 17:09.362
It's like I can see a little bit
of you in each one.

17:09.446 --> 17:11.072
♪ <i>I couldn't bear to wait...</i> ♪

17:11.156 --> 17:13.074
It's like I can...

17:13.158 --> 17:15.243
see how you see the world.

17:15.326 --> 17:17.579
♪ <i>My darling, be home soon...</i> ♪

17:17.662 --> 17:19.289
(laughs)

17:19.372 --> 17:21.291
(laughs) Um...

17:21.374 --> 17:23.168
well, that... that's it.

17:23.251 --> 17:27.213
-You... pretty much nailed it.
-(laughs softly)

17:27.297 --> 17:29.632
♪ <i>Of having you to talk to</i> ♪

17:29.716 --> 17:32.761
(camera shutter clicks)

17:33.762 --> 17:36.514
-♪ <i>And now...</i> ♪
-(exhales) Look at that beauty.

17:36.598 --> 17:38.558
-(camera shutter clicks)
-♪ <i>A quarter of my life</i> ♪

17:38.641 --> 17:40.477
♪ <i>Is almost past...</i> ♪

17:40.560 --> 17:42.729
All right, Nicholas Pearson,

17:42.812 --> 17:45.106
tell me your best Moon fact.

17:46.316 --> 17:47.984
Oh, I know a million facts.

17:48.068 --> 17:49.986
Do you want to know
about its gravitational pull?

17:50.070 --> 17:51.988
Tell me why you love her.

17:52.072 --> 17:53.907
♪ <i>Was the time that I spent</i>
<i>without you...</i> ♪

17:53.990 --> 17:55.367
(camera shutter clicks)

17:55.450 --> 17:58.036
-Why I love the Moon?
-Mm-hmm.

17:58.119 --> 18:02.707
Well, I love the Moon because...

18:02.791 --> 18:07.295
it's... Earth's personal satellite.

18:07.379 --> 18:09.339
♪ <i>I couldn't bear to wait</i>
<i>an extra minute...</i> ♪

18:09.422 --> 18:12.884
It's like the nightlight
we can all count on.

18:12.967 --> 18:14.511
(Sally laughs)

18:14.594 --> 18:16.763
It's always there...

18:16.846 --> 18:18.973
♪ <i>It's not just these few hours...</i> ♪

18:19.057 --> 18:21.518
...but different every night.

18:21.601 --> 18:24.229
And no matter where you are in the world,

18:24.312 --> 18:27.774
we're all looking up at that same Moon.

18:32.612 --> 18:33.947
I really want to kiss you now.

18:34.030 --> 18:36.741
(both laugh)

18:36.825 --> 18:38.868
♪ ♪

18:48.378 --> 18:49.838
(dog whimpering)

18:49.921 --> 18:51.464
♪ <i>So, darling</i> ♪

18:51.548 --> 18:55.093
-(barking)
-♪ <i>My darling, be home soon</i> ♪

18:55.176 --> 18:57.637
-(howls, barks)
-♪ <i>I couldn't bear to wait</i> ♪

18:57.721 --> 19:01.808
♪ <i>An extra minute if you dawdled</i> ♪

19:01.891 --> 19:05.353
♪ <i>My darling, be home soon</i> ♪

19:05.437 --> 19:07.605
♪ <i>It's not just these few hours</i> ♪

19:07.689 --> 19:10.483
♪ <i>But I've been waiting since I toddled</i> ♪

19:10.567 --> 19:15.905
♪ <i>For the great relief</i>
<i>of having you to talk to...</i> ♪

19:18.283 --> 19:21.161
I think I'm falling in love with you.

19:23.246 --> 19:25.290
(whispering):
You think or you know?

19:25.373 --> 19:28.209
I know.

19:28.293 --> 19:32.922
♪ <i>And see beyond the houses</i>
<i>and your eyes</i> ♪

19:33.006 --> 19:36.926
♪ <i>It's okay to shoot the moon...</i> ♪

19:38.219 --> 19:41.514
Mrs. Pearson, I consider myself
to be a Salisbury steak devotee,

19:41.598 --> 19:43.808
but this may... this may be...

19:43.892 --> 19:45.852
Yeah, I mean, that's the bite that did it.

19:45.935 --> 19:48.104
This is the best
Salisbury steak I've ever had.

19:48.188 --> 19:51.274
(laughs)
Thank you, Sally. Thank you.

19:51.358 --> 19:53.276
It was good, Mom.

19:53.360 --> 19:55.403
♪ <i>Of having you to talk to.</i> ♪

19:55.487 --> 19:58.156
I mean, that went better than
I could have ever imagined.

19:58.239 --> 20:01.534
-Yeah.
-It's like she hypnotized him.

20:01.618 --> 20:03.661
-I'm pinching myself, man.
-Yeah.

20:03.745 --> 20:05.622
Girl lights a fire in you.

20:05.705 --> 20:07.248
I'm happy for you, little brother.

20:07.332 --> 20:08.708
Honestly, I have no idea how it happened,

20:08.792 --> 20:10.210
but I know it's all thanks to you.

20:10.293 --> 20:11.961
No, come on.

20:12.045 --> 20:13.672
(laughing):
It is.

20:13.755 --> 20:15.507
SALLY:
You two must be up to no good.

20:15.590 --> 20:17.717
Can I take a picture

20:17.801 --> 20:19.803
of the famous Pittsburgh Pearson brothers?

20:19.886 --> 20:22.097
-Yeah.
-Famous.

20:22.180 --> 20:23.515
(both laugh)

20:23.598 --> 20:25.016
-Sure. Yeah.
-Sure.

20:25.100 --> 20:27.102
Okay.

20:28.103 --> 20:29.688
(sniffs)
Hmm.

20:29.771 --> 20:31.940
(Nicky laughs)

20:32.023 --> 20:34.651
Something...

20:34.734 --> 20:36.945
Oh. Here.

20:37.028 --> 20:38.822
(Nicky laughs)

20:38.905 --> 20:40.949
50 years from now,
you guys will look at this photo,

20:41.032 --> 20:44.703
and you will remember the taste
of your mom's Salisbury steak,

20:44.786 --> 20:46.788
and you'll be taken back
to this exact moment,

20:46.871 --> 20:48.748
this...

20:48.832 --> 20:51.626
-exact... feeling. -(both laugh)
-(camera shutter clicks)

20:57.298 --> 20:59.634
(sighs)

21:02.929 --> 21:05.056
Hey, Jack, um...

21:05.140 --> 21:07.892
I'm better now.

21:07.976 --> 21:10.603
I'm not the monster that you think I am.

21:23.241 --> 21:25.160
Yeah.

21:25.243 --> 21:27.662
(engine starts)

21:40.842 --> 21:41.843
Hi.

21:43.303 --> 21:46.056
Hi. (chuckles)

21:46.139 --> 21:49.434
I, uh, noticed that
you don't have headphones.

21:49.517 --> 21:52.437
(chuckles) Remember when people
used to talk on planes?

21:52.520 --> 21:53.938
-(weakly): Uh-huh.
-(chuckles)

21:56.858 --> 21:58.985
(sighs)
Is this your first time flying

21:59.069 --> 22:01.363
since COVID?

22:01.446 --> 22:03.865
Uh, no, uh...

22:03.948 --> 22:05.658
since 1971.

22:06.868 --> 22:07.994
Wow.

22:12.582 --> 22:15.627
I just can't believe
the Moon's a destination now.

22:15.710 --> 22:17.212
(Sally chuckles)

22:17.295 --> 22:20.840
Like Chicago or Toledo.

22:20.924 --> 22:23.885
-Huh.
-Okay, I have something mind-blowing

22:23.968 --> 22:26.346
to show you,
but you have to close your eyes.

22:26.429 --> 22:27.931
-Close my eyes?
-Close.

22:28.014 --> 22:29.849
-Okay.
-(paper rustling)

22:30.892 --> 22:32.477
Open them.

22:36.564 --> 22:39.484
-"Woodstock."
-Three days of peace,

22:39.567 --> 22:41.069
-love and music.
-Whoa.

22:41.152 --> 22:43.363
Jimi Hendrix
and Richie Havens are playing?

22:43.446 --> 22:46.199
I want to hear Janis sing the blues.

22:46.282 --> 22:48.284
I want to <i>see</i> Janis sing the blues.

22:48.368 --> 22:49.703
I...

22:49.786 --> 22:51.663
I... it sounds amazing.

22:51.746 --> 22:53.707
So, you'll come?

22:54.958 --> 22:56.292
Yeah.

22:56.376 --> 22:57.794
Yeah, I'll come.

22:57.877 --> 22:59.504
And then...

22:59.587 --> 23:01.840
after Woodstock...

23:01.923 --> 23:03.591
I think that you and I

23:03.675 --> 23:06.970
should just pack up Pearl
and hit the road.

23:07.053 --> 23:09.222
I think we should
just leave Pittsburgh behind

23:09.305 --> 23:10.765
and go to California.

23:11.766 --> 23:14.728
My cousin has this farm there
outside of San Francisco,

23:14.811 --> 23:17.856
and, well, he said that we could come,
and we could help out

23:17.939 --> 23:19.190
with the animals, and...

23:19.274 --> 23:21.359
And anytime we get bored, we could just

23:21.443 --> 23:24.112
pack up Pearl and hit the road.

23:24.195 --> 23:26.781
So, y-you want to drive to California

23:26.865 --> 23:29.200
and move there for-for good.

23:29.284 --> 23:32.620
"For good."
What does that mean, "for good"? (scoffs)

23:32.704 --> 23:36.207
My Grandma Pearl used to say,

23:36.291 --> 23:39.377
"Sweetie, you can do anything
you want with your life,

23:39.461 --> 23:41.463
or you can do nothing."

23:46.259 --> 23:47.719
(grunts softly)

23:47.802 --> 23:49.637
Yeah? Okay,

23:49.721 --> 23:50.764
so, we have to leave Wednesday night,

23:50.847 --> 23:52.098
because the festival starts on Friday,

23:52.182 --> 23:54.392
and we want to get a good spot.

23:54.476 --> 23:56.269
Okay.

23:56.353 --> 23:58.229
Okay,
I'll meet you here at 11:00

23:58.313 --> 24:00.899
right after my parents... go to sleep.

24:10.742 --> 24:12.243
JACK:
Look at these guys.

24:12.327 --> 24:13.703
-(chuckles): Jack!
-(Jack chuckles)

24:13.787 --> 24:15.330
-Is that you?
-How many years it been?

24:15.413 --> 24:16.998
-Oh, too many.
-JACK: Hey.

24:17.082 --> 24:19.709
-Sheehan's gonna be over the moon to see you.
-You think?

24:19.793 --> 24:21.878
You know, you were his favorite.

24:21.961 --> 24:23.296
-(scoffs) Go take a walk.
-(chuckles)

24:23.380 --> 24:24.756
-See you inside?
-Yeah.

24:24.839 --> 24:26.841
-I'll see you guys in there.
-All right.

24:34.808 --> 24:36.351
So, tell me about her.

24:36.434 --> 24:38.812
Oh, Carolina's, uh...

24:38.895 --> 24:41.106
smart, beautiful.

24:41.189 --> 24:43.566
She loves bicycles, of all things.

24:43.650 --> 24:46.403
Wants to ride bikes
in every city we travel to.

24:46.486 --> 24:48.988
That's funny.
Can't picture you on a bike.

24:49.072 --> 24:51.199
-(chuckles softly) It's not so bad.
-Yeah.

24:51.282 --> 24:53.910
Hurts your balls, but not so bad.

24:56.788 --> 24:58.581
Sir,

24:58.665 --> 25:01.459
I need to ask your advice on something.

25:01.543 --> 25:02.919
Um...

25:04.587 --> 25:06.548
There's this girl that I've been seeing.

25:06.631 --> 25:08.383
I've wanted to propose to her

25:08.466 --> 25:10.385
for a while now.

25:10.468 --> 25:11.803
And...

25:11.886 --> 25:14.264
You that afraid she'll say no?

25:14.347 --> 25:16.808
You're not <i>that</i> bad-looking, Pearson.

25:16.891 --> 25:20.395
♪ <i>Best not look at</i>
<i>everything you start...</i> ♪

25:20.478 --> 25:22.522
On our first date,

25:22.605 --> 25:26.067
she asked me about my time in Nam,

25:26.151 --> 25:28.570
and I lied to her.

25:29.571 --> 25:31.740
I told her I was just a mechanic.

25:31.823 --> 25:34.075
I mean, to this day, I-I still don't think

25:34.159 --> 25:37.037
she thinks I ever fired a weapon.

25:38.079 --> 25:39.914
Then, um,

25:39.998 --> 25:42.083
she asked me about my family.

25:42.167 --> 25:44.169
I lied to her, too.

25:44.252 --> 25:48.131
Uh... told her my brother died in the war.

25:48.214 --> 25:51.551
♪ <i>Getting ready on 30 now</i> ♪

25:51.634 --> 25:53.553
♪ <i>And you just want to say...</i> ♪

25:53.636 --> 25:57.432
I've had a million opportunities
to tell her the truth,

25:57.515 --> 26:00.143
and I just... never did.

26:00.226 --> 26:03.438
Couldn't find the words.
Never came out.

26:03.521 --> 26:05.648
Any excuse.

26:05.732 --> 26:07.484
Now it's just...

26:07.567 --> 26:10.153
Too much time has gone by.

26:14.282 --> 26:17.410
Carolina always knows
when I'm thinking about the war.

26:18.453 --> 26:20.163
I guess there's

26:20.246 --> 26:22.665
a certain look I get on my face
when it happens.

26:24.668 --> 26:27.170
Sometimes, she asks to hear about it.

26:27.253 --> 26:29.589
♪ <i>And I love her with...</i> ♪

26:29.673 --> 26:33.176
So, I tell her about the biggest waterfall

26:33.259 --> 26:35.553
I ever saw in Cao Bang Province.

26:36.596 --> 26:38.473
And how they always served us
that chipped beef

26:38.556 --> 26:40.809
that tasted like old pennies.

26:40.892 --> 26:43.812
♪ <i>It's the same</i>
<i>good behavior...</i> ♪

26:43.895 --> 26:45.522
The rest, I keep to myself.

26:45.605 --> 26:47.399
♪ <i>Yes, I will</i> ♪

26:47.482 --> 26:48.817
♪ <i>Go one day...</i> ♪

26:48.900 --> 26:50.777
Lot of these guys,

26:50.860 --> 26:52.570
their bodies are here, but their minds

26:52.654 --> 26:54.656
are still over there.

26:59.869 --> 27:03.373
<i>The trick is to not let yourself</i>
<i>get lost in it.</i>

27:06.167 --> 27:09.254
<i>Not to relive the same</i>
<i>horror show over and over.</i>

27:11.297 --> 27:13.675
<i>You owe this girl of yours</i>

27:13.758 --> 27:15.593
the future, not the past.

27:16.594 --> 27:20.015
-Are you sure? Because I...
-I'm sure. Yeah.

27:21.683 --> 27:23.643
Want my advice?

27:24.686 --> 27:26.730
Take every memory you have,

27:26.813 --> 27:29.566
photos, whatever, and lock it away.

27:29.649 --> 27:32.402
Visit it when you have one too many.

27:32.485 --> 27:35.822
But keep it separate
from the life you're building.

27:37.907 --> 27:40.744
Go propose to that girl, Pearson.

27:47.584 --> 27:49.586
(breathing deeply)

28:04.017 --> 28:05.727
(knock on door)

28:05.810 --> 28:08.313
Hey. I got you a Samsonite.

28:08.396 --> 28:10.023
-What?
-Yeah.

28:10.106 --> 28:12.650
I don't, I don't know much
about suitcases,

28:12.734 --> 28:15.779
but I-I feel like this thing's
gonna last forever.

28:15.862 --> 28:17.238
Aw.
(chuckles)

28:17.322 --> 28:20.116
I had to sneak it past Mom and Dad.

28:21.159 --> 28:23.453
Ooh.
(chuckles)

28:23.536 --> 28:25.497
Wow.

28:25.580 --> 28:27.916
This is great, man.
Thank you.

28:27.999 --> 28:29.876
-Yeah.
-Wow.

28:29.959 --> 28:32.504
-(suitcase closes)
-They know yet?

28:32.587 --> 28:35.507
No.
I was just gonna watch

28:35.590 --> 28:37.008
the astronauts' coming-home parade,

28:37.092 --> 28:40.679
and then I was gonna wait
for them to fall asleep

28:40.762 --> 28:41.930
and then go meet Sally.

28:43.098 --> 28:45.892
Truth is I-I didn't really want
to tell them unless I got there

28:45.975 --> 28:48.561
-just in case I got cold feet.
-Hey, come on.

28:48.645 --> 28:50.605
You're gonna have
the time of your life, kid.

28:50.689 --> 28:54.442
Open road, nice girl. I...

28:54.526 --> 28:57.362
(breathes deeply)

28:57.445 --> 29:00.240
Just remember to write me a postcard

29:00.323 --> 29:03.326
-every now and again, okay?
-(chuckles softly)

29:08.873 --> 29:12.502
Am I gonna stick out like
a sore thumb out in California?

29:14.087 --> 29:16.172
I-I... I don't surf.
I don't...

29:16.256 --> 29:18.800
I don't know any hippie lingo.
I...

29:18.883 --> 29:21.094
I feel like Sally's
probably just gonna dump me

29:21.177 --> 29:22.887
and then dump me somewhere along Route 66.

29:22.971 --> 29:24.639
-Like, I'm not...
-Nicky, stop.

29:24.723 --> 29:26.433
-I don't feel like it's a realistic...
-Stop. Just stop, man.

29:26.516 --> 29:29.519
Stop. Come on.
You're gonna be fine.

29:29.602 --> 29:31.396
I'm telling you, a...

29:31.479 --> 29:33.440
a girl like that,

29:33.523 --> 29:35.859
she asks me to go to California,

29:35.942 --> 29:38.945
I'm gone in a heartbeat.

29:41.489 --> 29:43.074
Thanks, Jack.

29:44.075 --> 29:46.745
<i>JOHN LINDSAY:</i>
<i>We are picking great moments.</i>

29:46.828 --> 29:49.414
<i>We have honored many voyagers before.</i>

29:49.497 --> 29:52.292
<i>Men who sailed around the world,</i>

29:52.375 --> 29:55.503
<i>men who flew alone across the ocean.</i>

29:55.587 --> 29:58.131
<i>But today, we honor three men who forged</i>

29:58.214 --> 29:59.549
<i>the first link</i>

29:59.632 --> 30:01.134
<i>between Earth and the stars.</i>

30:01.217 --> 30:04.512
<i>Today, we honor three men</i>

30:04.596 --> 30:06.765
<i>who have affirmed the best we have</i>

30:06.848 --> 30:07.891
<i>within us.</i>

30:07.974 --> 30:09.517
<i>And all that New York</i>

30:09.601 --> 30:10.977
<i>has given today--</i>

30:11.061 --> 30:12.896
<i>its cheers, its praise...</i>

30:12.979 --> 30:14.230
What?

30:14.314 --> 30:15.398
<i>...its glory...</i>

30:15.482 --> 30:17.525
No, nothing.

30:17.609 --> 30:19.903
I just...

30:19.986 --> 30:22.947
I can't believe I was your age
sitting with my old man,

30:23.031 --> 30:24.949
listening to the radio

30:25.033 --> 30:27.160
when Roosevelt come on,

30:27.243 --> 30:30.288
told us that Pearl Harbor got bombed.

30:30.372 --> 30:32.248
(clicks tongue)

30:32.332 --> 30:35.043
Everything changed.

30:35.126 --> 30:38.129
(chuckles):
Now, I'm the old man

30:38.213 --> 30:40.423
sitting here with my son,

30:40.507 --> 30:42.467
watching three Americans

30:42.550 --> 30:45.261
fly home from the Moon.

30:46.304 --> 30:49.307
Yeah.
Life's wild.

30:50.308 --> 30:52.394
-Here you go, sweetie.
-Hon, come.

30:52.477 --> 30:54.437
-Sit.
-Thanks, Mom.

30:54.521 --> 30:58.024
-Look how many people are at this parade.
-Oh.

30:58.108 --> 30:59.484
<i>...for your support,</i>

30:59.567 --> 31:04.197
<i>support that made our mission possible.</i>

31:04.280 --> 31:08.410
<i>It's a privilege for me</i>
<i>to accept the honor...</i>

31:18.336 --> 31:20.255
(knock on window)

31:20.338 --> 31:22.841
-Hi.
-You're gonna have

31:22.924 --> 31:24.843
to move your van to a new spot tomorrow.

31:24.926 --> 31:26.845
Okay?
You've been parked here too long.

31:26.928 --> 31:29.764
Sure.
I was about to leave anyway.

31:50.744 --> 31:53.747
-♪ ♪
-(speaking quietly)

32:02.881 --> 32:05.091
-Thanks.
-Yep.

32:09.012 --> 32:11.473
♪ ♪

32:40.126 --> 32:43.463
(two car doors closing)

32:43.546 --> 32:45.548
(engine starts)

32:50.720 --> 32:52.222
It was nothing.

33:02.691 --> 33:04.651
It's just...

33:04.734 --> 33:07.445
-tiny fancy fish.
-(Madison chuckles)

33:07.529 --> 33:10.031
So, you-you just... you just went online

33:10.115 --> 33:13.618
and you booked a plane ticket
to Los Angeles, just...?

33:13.702 --> 33:15.620
Hey, you named your son after me, kid.

33:15.704 --> 33:17.288
I had to come.

33:17.372 --> 33:19.541
(chuckles)

33:19.624 --> 33:21.418
-I am gonna say good night.
-Yeah?

33:21.501 --> 33:23.211
Mm-hmm.
I'm gonna feed the twins,

33:23.294 --> 33:26.214
and then pass out from exhaustion.

33:26.297 --> 33:29.426
Uh, I'm sorry that
I just showed up unannounced.

33:29.509 --> 33:31.052
I recognize it's kind of weird.

33:31.136 --> 33:34.472
No. No, Kevin was just saying
he missed having family around,

33:34.556 --> 33:38.393
and then you showed up,
so that's a good weird in my book.

33:38.476 --> 33:40.395
-(chuckles)
-I'll let you guys catch up.

33:40.478 --> 33:42.480
-Good night. -Good night.
-Good night.

33:46.401 --> 33:48.611
Well, a lot's happened
since I saw you in the flesh.

33:48.695 --> 33:50.030
(chuckles)

33:50.113 --> 33:52.657
Yeah.
Yeah, a lot has happened.

33:52.741 --> 33:55.035
And I-I can't wait for you
to meet Nick and Franny.

33:55.118 --> 33:57.037
I mean, oh, they're perfect.

33:57.120 --> 33:58.872
It's, like, you stare into their eyes,

33:58.955 --> 34:01.624
and it's like there's nothing
wrong in the world, you know?

34:01.708 --> 34:03.793
-Yeah?
-Yeah. Yeah.

34:03.877 --> 34:05.712
Yeah, it's really something.

34:05.795 --> 34:08.173
Oh, and I want to take you
to this dog park.

34:08.256 --> 34:10.175
It's right around the corner.
We'll go tomorrow.

34:10.258 --> 34:12.177
We take the twins there
every morning, and we just,

34:12.260 --> 34:14.804
we go there and we watch
the dogs just kind of run amok.

34:14.888 --> 34:17.015
You know?
It's like a Pixar film, it's great.

34:17.098 --> 34:18.391
You like dogs, right?
Didn't you say

34:18.475 --> 34:20.185
you worked at a vet clinic before the war?

34:20.268 --> 34:22.812
-Yeah, I did.
-Yeah. Yeah.

34:22.896 --> 34:25.690
Oh. And-and we got to figure out
what it is

34:25.774 --> 34:27.400
that you want them to call you.

34:27.484 --> 34:29.444
Uh, uh, it's not "Grandpa," obviously,

34:29.527 --> 34:31.237
but, uh, it could be...

34:31.321 --> 34:34.407
it could be "Chief," it could be "Toot"

34:34.491 --> 34:35.784
or-or, um...

34:35.867 --> 34:37.827
it could-- "Pops."

34:41.748 --> 34:43.458
You-you must be exhausted.

34:43.541 --> 34:45.168
You're probably dead tired
from the traveling, I would imagine.

34:45.251 --> 34:47.712
You want me to go make up your bed,
get that ready for you?

34:47.796 --> 34:50.131
-Good idea.
-How about... Yeah, I'll do that for you.

34:51.675 --> 34:53.134
(exhales)

34:58.181 --> 35:00.892
(taking deep breaths)

35:18.076 --> 35:19.411
(line ringing)

35:19.494 --> 35:21.496
(buzzing)

35:23.081 --> 35:25.000
It's 4:00 a.m. here, old man.

35:25.083 --> 35:27.335
Ah, you suck at sleeping just like I do.

35:27.419 --> 35:30.338
<i>-Oh, I knew you'd be up.</i>
-It's true.

35:30.422 --> 35:31.798
What's going on?

35:31.881 --> 35:34.092
(sighs)

35:34.175 --> 35:38.263
I'm thinking that
this whole thing was a mistake.

35:38.346 --> 35:40.056
<i>You know, I thought that the plane ride</i>

35:40.140 --> 35:41.433
<i>would be the hard part,</i>

35:41.516 --> 35:44.019
but now I'm thinking
I might just sneak out of here

35:44.102 --> 35:45.979
while everybody's asleep, and I'll just,

35:46.062 --> 35:47.772
you know, I'll call Kevin

35:47.856 --> 35:50.608
<i>-once I land...</i>
-Are you certifiably insane?

35:50.692 --> 35:52.610
It's just different now that I'm here.

35:52.694 --> 35:55.238
I mean, Jack's kid named his kid after me.

35:55.321 --> 35:58.533
I mean... (exhales)
God, Jack must be rolling in his grave

35:58.616 --> 36:00.201
around that one.

36:00.285 --> 36:02.912
Now the kid wants me to go to the park

36:02.996 --> 36:05.790
and take pictures and be "Grandpa."

36:05.874 --> 36:09.085
<i>-Ugh, it's too much.</i>
-Nicky...

36:09.169 --> 36:11.338
(takes deep breath)

36:11.421 --> 36:13.882
You've hated yourself for so long,

36:13.965 --> 36:16.009
and now you have all this love
coming at you,

36:16.092 --> 36:18.595
and it feels weird,
and you want to go AWOL.

36:18.678 --> 36:20.597
<i>And then what,</i>
<i>go back to your trailer alone</i>

36:20.680 --> 36:23.808
<i>and stare at the same</i>
<i>plot of land until you die?</i>

36:23.892 --> 36:25.477
I...

36:25.560 --> 36:29.439
I didn't know this brother of yours,

36:29.522 --> 36:32.400
<i>but I do know two pretty decent men</i>

36:32.484 --> 36:34.778
<i>who have spent their lives</i>

36:34.861 --> 36:37.572
<i>wondering if he would be proud of them.</i>

36:38.782 --> 36:41.493
Deep down...

36:41.576 --> 36:44.788
don't you think
he'd be proud of you, Nicky?

36:44.871 --> 36:46.581
<i>Took a while, but you made it.</i>

36:46.664 --> 36:49.084
<i>You made it all the way to California.</i>

36:58.134 --> 36:59.678
Hey there, babies.

37:01.012 --> 37:04.015
Don't worry, I won't get too close.

37:05.225 --> 37:08.728
FYI, I've been vaccinated, twice.

37:10.480 --> 37:12.899
Um, I-I...

37:12.982 --> 37:16.778
I made these really special gifts for you,

37:16.861 --> 37:19.823
but, um, this country is kind of idiotic

37:19.906 --> 37:22.117
about its rules sometimes, so I got you...

37:22.200 --> 37:24.244
I got you these instead.

37:25.328 --> 37:28.248
Well, my favorite John Grisham novels.

37:28.331 --> 37:30.417
That's <i>The Firm.</i>

37:30.500 --> 37:32.669
And, uh...

37:32.752 --> 37:35.171
and <i>The Rainmaker.</i>

37:35.255 --> 37:37.424
Uh, I'm sorry they're in paperback.

37:37.507 --> 37:40.385
It's the only thing they had
at the airport gift shop.

37:41.553 --> 37:42.512
(fussing quietly)

37:42.595 --> 37:45.598
I-I jotted some things down in...

37:45.682 --> 37:46.766
in the book.

37:46.850 --> 37:49.853
Uh, no great words of wisdom.

37:51.062 --> 37:52.105
But...

37:52.188 --> 37:54.107
when you're an old man

37:54.190 --> 37:57.819
and you're looking out a plane window...

37:57.902 --> 37:59.362
(takes deep breath)

37:59.446 --> 38:01.573
...you think about all the

38:01.656 --> 38:04.367
mistakes you make in life.

38:24.220 --> 38:25.638
<i>I lived alone.</i>

38:25.722 --> 38:29.684
Every day, the same routine for 50 years.

38:32.020 --> 38:34.564
But then...

38:34.647 --> 38:38.193
I got an invitation to meet you two.

38:38.276 --> 38:39.944
And you know,

38:40.028 --> 38:42.197
you know what it got me thinking about?

38:44.366 --> 38:47.744
It got me thinking about the Moon.

38:47.827 --> 38:52.707
July 20, 1969...

38:54.876 --> 38:57.962
...I watched a man walk on the Moon.

38:58.046 --> 39:02.217
One day, we'd never been to the Moon.

39:02.300 --> 39:06.721
It was impossible to even fathom
walking on it.

39:06.805 --> 39:09.265
And the next day,

39:09.349 --> 39:11.351
we're walking on it.

39:13.353 --> 39:17.023
The impossible became possible,

39:17.107 --> 39:19.150
just like that.

39:22.070 --> 39:23.571
(baby coos)

39:25.073 --> 39:27.617
For 50 years,

39:27.701 --> 39:30.161
I lived in a trailer.

39:30.245 --> 39:33.581
A trailer that went nowhere.

39:33.665 --> 39:36.668
Whatever the opposite is of an astronaut,

39:36.751 --> 39:39.170
that-that's...
(scoffs)

39:39.254 --> 39:42.132
That's what I became.

39:44.759 --> 39:47.721
And then I got that invitation

39:47.804 --> 39:51.016
in the mail...

39:51.099 --> 39:53.643
for a Zoom...
(laughs)

39:53.727 --> 39:55.770
...apparently, whatever the hell that is.

39:57.689 --> 40:00.275
But an invitation to meet

40:00.358 --> 40:03.319
my great-nephew

40:03.403 --> 40:05.155
and my great-niece.

40:05.238 --> 40:07.282
(cooing)

40:11.995 --> 40:14.789
My big brother's grandchildren.

40:21.463 --> 40:26.051
I've lived alone a really long time,

40:26.134 --> 40:28.470
and I've been...

40:28.553 --> 40:30.889
I've been stuck.

40:33.516 --> 40:36.353
And...

40:36.436 --> 40:38.897
anything...

40:38.980 --> 40:42.734
anything good
that would ever happen to me,

40:42.817 --> 40:46.905
it just seemed...

40:46.988 --> 40:49.074
it just seemed impossible.

40:52.285 --> 40:54.954
But here I am.
I made it.

40:57.540 --> 41:00.210
You two--

41:00.293 --> 41:02.629
You two were my Moon.

41:03.672 --> 41:06.049
(coos, grunts)

41:08.218 --> 41:11.429
Okay, that's it.
(exhales)

41:14.557 --> 41:16.267
You just call me "Uncle Nicky," okay?

41:16.351 --> 41:18.269
No stupid nicknames.

41:21.648 --> 41:23.608
-Okay?
-(cooing)

41:25.860 --> 41:27.862
("Lonely People" by America begins)

41:36.996 --> 41:38.456
(baby coos)

